300":"1300","1234":"1234","1255":"1255","1233":"1233","1265":"1265","1320":"1320","about 1235":"about 1235","about 1265":"about 1265","Hodnet, Shropshire, England":"Hodnet, Shropshire, England","Northampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Coton, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, England","Cotton, Cheshire, England":"Cotton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cotton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called from Old English <i>(æt) cotum</i> (dative plural of <i>cot</i>) ‘at the cottages or huts’ (or sometimes possibly from a Middle English plural, <i>coten</i>). Examples include Coton (Cambridgeshire, Northamptonshire, Staffordshire), Cottam (East Yorkshire, Lancashire, Nottinghamshire), and Cotham (Nottinghamshire). Particularly common in Staffordshire.","French: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Nicolas</i> (see   Nicholas  ), derived via <i>Nicot</i>, or of the personal name   Jacques  , derived via <i>Jacot</i>.","History: John Cotton (1584–1652) was a noted Puritan preacher, who landed at Boston, MA, from London in 1633 and became leader of the Congregationalists in America."],"variants":[{"name":"Cotten","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Cotton  .","Altered form of German <b>Kotten</b>, a habitational name from any of several places so named in Rhineland, Westphalia, Silesia, etc., or perhaps an American shortened form of composite German surnames such as <b>Kottenhagen</b>, <b>Kottenhoff</b>, <b>Kottenkamp</b> (see   Koth  )."]},{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["English (southwestern England and south Wales) and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Nicholas</i> (from Latin <i>Nicolaus</i>, from Greek <i>Nikolaos</i>, from <i>nikān</i> ‘to conquer’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’). Forms with <i>-ch-</i> are due to hypercorrection (compare   Anthony  ). The name in various vernacular forms was popular among Christians throughout Europe in the Middle Ages, largely as a result of the fame of a 4th-century Lycian bishop, about whom a large number of legends grew up, and who was venerated in the Orthodox Church as well as the Catholic. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Croatian and Serbian <b>Nikolić</b> (see   Nikolic  ), Greek <b>Papanikolaou</b> ‘(son of) Nicholas the priest’ and   Nikolopoulos  . Compare   Nickolas  .","History: The colonial official and revolutionary patriot Robert Carter Nicholas was from a prominent VA family on both sides. His father was a British navy surgeon who emigrated <i>c.</i> 1700 from Lancashire, England, to Williamsburg, VA."]},{"name":"Cotham","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Cotton  ."]},{"name":"Cottom","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Cotton  ."]},{"name":"Cottam","meanings":["English (Midlands and northern England): variant of   Cotton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"FitzSimmon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of <b>Fitzsimon</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + either of the personal names <i>Simon</i> or <i>Sigmund</i> (see   Simon  ), ‘son of <i>Simon</i> or <i>Sigmund</i>’. The name is also found in the Gaelicized form <b>Mac Síomóin</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."]},{"name":"Fitzsimons","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Caitlin, Niamh.","Irish: variant of   Fitzsimmons  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":24,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":55,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William FitzSimmon de Cotton was born about 1235, in Coton, Shropshire, England, his father, Sir Simon FitzWilliam de Cotton, was 41 and his mother, Enid Grosvenor de Maatenloch, was 46. He married Enid Grosvenor de Maatenloch about 1250, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1290, in his hometown, at the age of 56."},"et":{"about 1235–1290":"umbes 1235–1290","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1233–Male":"1233–Surnud","1235–1290":"1235–1290","1234–1302":"1234–1302","1190–1270":"1190–1270","1255–1300":"1255–1300","1265–1320":"1265–1320","1195–Male":"1195–Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1250":"umbes 1250","1195":"1195","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1302":"1302","1225":"1225","about 1228":"umbes 1228","1235":"1235","1300":"1300","1234":"1234","1255":"1255","1233":"1233","1265":"1265","1320":"1320","about 1235":"umbes 1235","about 1265":"umbes 1265","Hodnet, Shropshire, England":"Hodnet, Shropshire, England","Northampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","Coton, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, England","Cotton, Cheshire, England":"Cotton, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1235–1290":"noin 1235–1290","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1233–Male":"1233–Kuollut","1235–1290":"1235–1290","1234–1302":"1234–1302","1190–1270":"1190–1270","1255–1300":"1255–1300","1265–1320":"1265–1320","1195–Male":"1195–Kuollut","1190":"1190","about 1250":"noin 1250","1195":"1195","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1302":"1302","1225":"1225","about 1228":"noin 1228","1235":"1235","1300":"1300","1234":"1234","1255":"1255","1233":"1233","1265":"1265","1320":"1320","